YES! With C++11, you can make a variadic function. Here is the code.

    int sum(int n, ...){
    
       va_list list;
       va_start(list ,n);

       int x;

       int s=0;

       for(int i=0; i&lt;n; i++){
           x = va_arg(list,int);
           s+=x;
       }

     return s;
    }

In main, you can call `sum(2, 2, 5)`. 

The first parameter is the number of parameter you have.

Also, you can call `sum(3, 3, 5, 10)` which will return 18.

In C++11 and later, you can use a [variadic template](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/parameter_pack):

```c++
int sum(int value) {
	return value;
}

template&lt;typename... Targs&gt;
int sum(int value, Targs... Fargs) {
	return value + sum(Fargs...);
}

sum(2,5);
sum(3,5,10);
```

[Live demo](http://ideone.com/cZKAmX)

In C++17 and later, you can use a fold expression to remove the recursion:

```c++
template&lt;typename... Targs&gt;
int sum(Targs... Fargs) {
	return (Fargs + ...);
}
```

[Live demo](http://ideone.com/xJ0GDk)

Alternatively, in C++11 and later, you can use `std::initializer_list`:

```c++
#include &lt;initializer_list&gt;

int sum(std::initializer_list&lt;int&gt; values) {
	int result = 0;
	for (int value : values) {
		result += value;
	}
	return result;
}

sum({2,5});
sum({3,5,10});
```

[Live demo](http://ideone.com/T5j3dN)

And then use [`std::accumulate()`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/accumulate) to remove the manual loop:

```c++
#include &lt;initializer_list&gt;
#include &lt;numeric&gt;

int sum(std::initializer_list&lt;int&gt; values) {
	return std::accumulate(values.begin(), values.end(), 0);
}
```

[Live demo](http://ideone.com/eLHsNU)

If, for some reason, you are not using a C++11 compiler, then you can use an array instead:

```c++
template&lt;size_t N&gt;
int sum(int (&amp;values)[N]) {
	int result = 0;
	for (int i = 0; i &lt; N; ++i) {
		result += values[i];
	}
	return result;
}

int values[] = {2,5};
sum(values);

int values2[] = {3,5,10};
sum(values2);
```

[Live demo](http://ideone.com/b8qvAg)

