answers.body_markdown:
The relationship between both clubs and events are against the *user*, not each other. Also, as both relationships are many-to-many, you would benefit from two [bridging tables][1]; one between users and clubs, and the other between users and events:

&lt;h3&gt;&lt;code&gt;user_clubs&lt;/code&gt; table:&lt;/h3&gt;

    user_id  |  club_id   |  payment_method
    ---------------------------------------
        1    |     1      |  &#39;Visa&#39;
        2    |     1      |  &#39;Visa&#39;
        2    |     2      |  &#39;Mastercard&#39;

&lt;h3&gt;&lt;code&gt;user_events&lt;/code&gt; table:&lt;/h3&gt;
    user_id  |  club_id   |  payment_method
    ---------------------------------------
        1    |     1      |  &#39;Visa&#39;
        2    |     1      |  &#39;Visa&#39;
        2    |     2      |  &#39;Mastercard&#39;
    
&lt;sup&gt;These are in addition to `user`, `clubs` and `events` tables.&lt;/sup&gt;

As you can see, this allows users to join multiple clubs and attend multiple events, while also allowing clubs and events to host multiple users. This also completely eliminates the need for the `payment` table entirely, by shifting the only missing column (`payment_method`) onto the two bridging tables. The `membership_fees` map out to the `amount`, so it is no longer needed.

From here, you can query **all** of the relevant information about a particular user (or club / event) by *joining* the tables together in your query. For example, if you want all info about a user:

    SELECT * FROM user
             INNER JOIN user_clubs ON user.id = user_clubs.user_id
             INNER JOIN clubs ON user_clubs.club_id = clubs.id
             INNER JOIN user_events ON user.id = user_events.user_id
             INNER JOIN events ON user_events.user_id = club.id
    WHERE user.id = &#39;1&#39;

This will give you all information about a user; the clubs they belong to, the events they attend, the respective fees, and how the user paid those fees.

  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_entity

